Problem: Given an array nums and a window size k, return the maximum element in every sliding window of size k.

Example:
nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7]
k = 3

Windows:
[1  3 -1] -3  5  3  6  7   -> 3
 1 [3 -1 -3] 5  3  6  7   -> 3
 1  3 [-1 -3 5] 3  6  7   -> 5
 1  3 -1 [-3 5 3] 6  7    -> 5
 1  3 -1 -3 [5 3 6] 7     -> 6
 1  3 -1 -3 5 [3 6 7]     -> 7

Answer = [3,3,5,5,6,7]
1. Brute Force

For every window of size k, scan all k elements and find the maximum.

Time Complexity
Number of windows = n - k + 1
Finding max for each window = O(k)

Total: O((n-k+1) * k) ≈ O(nk)

Code
class Solution {
    public int[] maxSlidingWindow(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n - k + 1];

        for (int i = 0; i <= n - k; i++) {
            int max = nums[i];

            for (int j = i; j < i + k; j++) {
                max = Math.max(max, nums[j]);
            }

            ans[i] = max;
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

2. Sliding Window using PriorityQueue (Max Heap)

Maintain a max heap storing {value, index}.

Add current element.
Remove elements whose indices are outside the current window.
Heap top is the maximum.
Time Complexity
Insert: O(log k)
Remove: O(log k)
Total: O(n log k)

Code
class Solution {
    public int[] maxSlidingWindow(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n - k + 1];

        PriorityQueue<int[]> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(
            (a, b) -> b[0] - a[0]
        );

        int idx = 0;

        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {

            pq.offer(new int[]{nums[j], j});

            while (pq.peek()[1] <= j - k) {
                pq.poll();
            }

            if (j >= k - 1) {
                ans[idx++] = pq.peek()[0];
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

3. Optimal: Monotonic Deque (Most Asked)
Idea

Maintain a deque of indices such that:

Elements are stored in decreasing order of values.
Front always contains the index of the maximum element.

For every new element:

Remove indices that are out of the current window.
Remove all smaller elements from the back (they can never become maximum).
Add current index.
Once window size becomes k, the front of deque is the answer.
Why remove smaller elements?

Suppose:

nums = [3, 1, 5]

When 5 arrives:

1 can never be maximum because 5 is larger and comes later.
3 can also never be maximum for any future window containing 5.

So remove both and keep only 5.

Time Complexity
Every element is inserted once and removed once.
Total operations ≤ 2n.

Time: O(n)
Space: O(k)

Code (Optimal)
class Solution {
    public int[] maxSlidingWindow(int[] nums, int k) {

        int n = nums.length;
        int[] ans = new int[n - k + 1];

        Deque<Integer> dq = new LinkedList<>();
        int idx = 0;

        for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {

            // Remove indices outside the window
            while (!dq.isEmpty() && dq.peekFirst() <= j - k) {
                dq.pollFirst();
            }

            // Remove smaller elements
            while (!dq.isEmpty() &&
                   nums[dq.peekLast()] < nums[j]) {
                dq.pollLast();
            }

            // Add current index
            dq.offerLast(j);

            // Window of size k formed
            if (j >= k - 1) {
                ans[idx++] = nums[dq.peekFirst()];
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

